Don’t feel like spending 25$ pp and doing the full Statue of Liberty tour? 

Get beautiful views of the Statue of Liberty for free! 
Take the Staten Island ferry from Whitehall Ferry terminal in Manhattan. The ferry takes you to Staten Island and you can get the next ferry back to the City. Ferry’s run every 15-20min and is totally free. TIP: try to avoid rush hours. 
And you still get very beautiful views of the statue as seen in this video. Great for when you are a big group and have a tight schedule.

I am very conscious about my skincare routine, especially when TRAVELING! 

I have super sensitive skin and I am so careful about what goes on it! And when traveling we have so many things to consider such as the dryness in the air during a flight, weather and environmental changes - which can cause our skin to react. 

I am not a dermatologist, but over the years and with my experience traveling, I have found what works for me to make sure my skin is getting what it needs to avoid dryness, and a breakout. 

On long flights I usually bring a moisturizing face mask (no matter how funny it might look to others) but a little TLC before landing could go a long way! 

I almost always avoid makeup on flights, especially long ones - because due to high altitudes on a plane, your pores are dilated. That is exactly why it’s the perfect time to get that face mask out as your pores are ready to take in all that nutrients and moisture! 

And a good skincare routine on your trip is a must because you will be changing your eating, sleeping and drinking habits, which all shows through our skin. 

I have been using @versed for the past few months and my skin has been loving it! It’s great for my sensitive skin and it comes in travel sizes, which is perfect to keep your luggage light. Like I said, I am very picky about what goes on my skin and therefore I wanted to try it for a few months before I recommended it! This one gets a thumbs up for me 👍🏼

We went to Philly for the infamous Philly Cheesesteak sandwich! 

This was by far the most impromptu trip ever!!! 

I was speaking to my friends and the idea of going to Philly was thrown out there in the chat. Decided by 12 that we are in-fact going to Philly. Found @amtrak tickets for 25$ each. Packed, and was on the way to Philly by 4pm. 

As soon as we arrived, we went to have a Philly Cheesesteak sandwich of course from @angelos_pizzeria_south_philly which was absolutely amazing!!! 

While we were having our sandwich we were searching Airbnbs to stay the night 😂 and we found an amazing one luckily. Checked-in and then went to checkout a rooftop bar, which i definitely recommend for sunset time @bok_bar 

We also tried a few other cheesesteak sandwiches at different places (I know we went overboard) but Angelo’s was by far the fav! 

The next day we spent the day exploring and saw the Liberty bell, the Rocky statue and steps and went to @surayaphilly which is now officially one of my fav Lebanese food spots that I’ve been to in the US. 

So long story short, I guess we will now be driving back to Philly for not only a Philly cheesesteak sandwich, but also Lebanese food! 😂 YOLO @visitphilly 

I guess we now have a funny story to tell 🤷🏻‍♀️
Now I know how easy it is to escape the city and head to Philly. So if you ever want a change in scenery, here you go -> you have Philly as an option. It is only a 1.5 hr train ride and you can get really affordable tickets.

I’ve received a lot of questions about traveling with your dog - 
Each airline and destination have their specific requirements for flying with your dog. Here is what we required in order to fly to Rio with Rio. 

A checkup with your local vet 10 days before your flight and your vet will check that all vaccines are up to date, and submit all necessary documents to the USDA , which is then sent back ahead of your flight by email (a hard copy is not required for travel to Brazil). And you are all set for your trip. You then need to set up a vet appointment in Brazil 5 days before flying back (they need to check for screw worm) and you submit all documents online, signed by the vet. 

But please note that travel requirements change frequently, so make sure to keep checking back with the cdc.
